<p><strong>Q2: Is homemade laundry detergent safe for HE (high-efficiency) machines?</strong><strong><br></strong>Yes! There is a lot of low-sudsing homemade detergent which is ideal to run in HE machines provided that the quantity is correct.</p>

<p><strong>Q3: Can I make a fragrance-free laundry detergent at home?<br></strong>Absolutely. All you have to do is avoid the essential oils and use an unscented soap base to make it 100% fragrance-free.</p>

<p><strong>Q4: How much money can I save with DIY laundry detergent?</strong><strong><br></strong>Commercial brands have price tags of $0.20 or more, whereas you can make homemade choices as cheap as $0.05 per load saving you up to 150 bucks a year on a family of four.</p>

<p><strong>Q5: What is the most toxic laundry detergent to avoid?<br></strong>The most dangerous brands are those that use chemicals like 1,4-dioxane, formaldehyde and artificial fragrances. A product\'s label should always be compared before buying.</p>

<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong><strong>Conclusion</strong></strong></h2>

<p>It is indeed more of a wise choice of lifestyle rather than a trend to shift to homemade laundry detergent. It can provide cleaner garments and even safer skin, with major savings, and it is greener for the environment. It is a simple successful switch that you can make today with a few simple ingredients and a little know-how to switch out of the chemically laden commercial brands without a drop of chemical in sight. Your laundry—and your skin—will thank you.</p>

